Title: Yiwu Commodities Market
Content:
A wholesale market frequented by international buyers.

KWB's Highlights:
  • Whilst most factories require you to buy in bulk, in the Yiwu Commodities Market you can buy from China with no minimum quantities.
  • There are countless categories divided into 5 districts (a.k.a. buildings).
  • Be ready to walk for 8 hours a day.
  • We don't know of anything interesting to see in the city, looks like this is a place to do business and move on.
  • Be impressed by the sheer amount of luxury and exotic cars.
  • Chinese police sometimes seem to be wary of Muslims. If stopped, we recommend you explain which country you are from and that you are Jewish (You Tai, in Mandarin). In our experience that works, since it answers what the cops are really asking.
  • Be sure to stop by Chabad Yiwu, not only because it's the only option in town, but because it's awesome.
  • Check out the hotels we recommend.
  • KWB can recommend a trade agent which may go with you to the fair, help you navigate, translate and export your goods. Just ask us.
Content_Tagline: A wholesale market frequented by international buyers.
Content_Description:
KWB’s Highlights:

Whilst most factories require you to buy in bulk, in the Yiwu Commodities Market you can buy from China with no minimum quantities.
There are countless categories divided into 5 districts (a.k.a. buildings).
Be ready to walk for 8 hours a day.
We don’t know of anything interesting to see in the city, looks like this is a place to do business and move on.
Be impressed by the sheer amount of luxury and exotic cars.
Chinese police sometimes seem to be wary of Muslims. If stopped, we recommend you explain which country you are from and that you are Jewish (You Tai, in Mandarin). In our experience that works, since it answers what the cops are really asking.
Be sure to stop by Chabad Yiwu, not only because it’s the only option in town, but because it’s awesome.
Check out the hotels we recommend.
KWB can recommend a trade agent which may go with you to the fair, help you navigate, translate and export your goods. Just ask us.

Title: Chabad of Chengdu, China
Content:

KWB's Highlights:
  • Modern, welcoming Chabad House.
  • For Shabbat, you can join to celebrate with delicious meals, in a warm atmosphere. From the Kiddush and Challah to the meaningful discussion and inspiring songs.
  • Kindly make a reservation so they can be properly prepared for all guests.
  • On Friday evenings, Arvit services begin fifteen minutes after candle lighting. Followed by the Shabbat meal. For Chengdu candle lighting times, please, click here.
  • If you are looking for a hotel within walking distance to the Chabad House, click here.
  • Due to Chinese government regulations,  events are restricted to foreign passport holders and their families.
  • Kosher food information, click here.
  • Sarah's Kitchen is Chengdu's first Kosher restaurant located at the Chabad Jewish Center of Chengdu. Opens daily and has an option for delivery throughout the city.  Offers authentic Chinese dishes as well as traditional Jewish dishes in a warm atmosphere.
  • There is currently no Mikvah in Chengdu. They are in the process of looking for a property and a donor so Chengdu can have a Mikvah of its own. Click here to donate.

Title: Tsukiji Market (Tokyo)
Content:
Sprawling wholesale fish market with an array of seafood & viewing areas for a popular tuna auction.

KWB's Highlights:
  • The world's largest, busiest fish market has long been a favourite destination for jet-lagged tourists with predawn hours to fill. But the main reason for going at 5 a.m. is to catch the live tuna auctions.
  • It will be on a first-come, first-serve basis, and limited to 120 people, admitted in two shifts of 60. You can register starting at 4:30 a.m. at the fish information centre inside the Kachidoki Gate off Harumi Street.
  • If you prefer to do your exploring at a more reasonable hour, keep in mind that by 9 a.m., business will have already started to wind down. You'll still see fishmongers filleting the day's catch, but you won't have to dodge so many trucks and trolleys.
  • If the wholesale market smells too fishy for you, a less pungent alternative is Tsukiji's outer market, a warren of narrow streets packed with stalls selling fresh seafood and other speciality items, such as real wasabi.
  • You can buy bowls and sashimi knives there too. Right in the thick of it is the reliably superb Sushizanmai's honten (main branch), open 24 hours.
A few more general rules for visiting Tsukiji Market
  • Since Tsukiji Market is a site where serious business is conducted, it is important for visitors not to interfere with the action by adhering to the following additional rules:
  • Do not enter areas restricted to authorised personnel!
  • Do not obstruct traffic!
  • Do not bring large bags or suitcases into the market!
  • Do not enter the market in high heeled shoes or sandals!
  • Do not bring small children or pets!
  • Do not smoke in the market!
  • Do not touch anything!
Content_Tagline: Sprawling wholesale fish market with an array of seafood & viewing areas for a popular tuna auction.
Content_Description:
KWB’s Highlights:

The world’s largest, busiest fish market has long been a favourite destination for jet-lagged tourists with predawn hours to fill. But the main reason for going at 5 a.m. is to catch the live tuna auctions.
It will be on a first-come, first-serve basis, and limited to 120 people, admitted in two shifts of 60. You can register starting at 4:30 a.m. at the fish information centre inside the Kachidoki Gate off Harumi Street.
If you prefer to do your exploring at a more reasonable hour, keep in mind that by 9 a.m., business will have already started to wind down. You’ll still see fishmongers filleting the day’s catch, but you won’t have to dodge so many trucks and trolleys.
If the wholesale market smells too fishy for you, a less pungent alternative is Tsukiji’s outer market, a warren of narrow streets packed with stalls selling fresh seafood and other speciality items, such as real wasabi.
You can buy bowls and sashimi knives there too. Right in the thick of it is the reliably superb Sushizanmai’s honten (main branch), open 24 hours.

Since Tsukiji Market is a site where serious business is conducted, it is important for visitors not to interfere with the action by adhering to the following additional rules:
Do not enter areas restricted to authorised personnel!

Do not enter the market in high heeled shoes or sandals!
Do not bring small children or pets!

Title: Glick's Kosher Market
Content:
Glicks provides strictly Kosher deli meats, shiva, appetising prepared foods, delicatessen and also provides catering in Delray Beach, FL.

KWB’s Highlights:
  • Glicks Legacy of Fine Foods started with a simple family-run Kosher meat market in Brooklyn, New York.
  • In the early 1900's Sam Glick and his siblings emigrated from Russia and opened the first Glick Bros. Kosher Market. When Sam passed on, his wife Rachel and her sons Harold, Herman, and son-in-law, Jules Goldberg, took control of the business.
  • Because of their commitment to Superior Quality Meats, Glick Bros. grew to become the largest Kosher Meat chains in New York. By the mid-1900’s, there were more than twenty Glick Bros. stores in operation throughout New York.
  • In 1995, Jules son Gary relocated to south Florida with his family. Within a year Gary and his wife, Linda, built and opened Glicks Kosher Market in Delray Beach.
  • By implementing all that he had learned from working with his father for over twenty years, the store was an instant success.
  • In less than four years, Gary moved Glicks to a new location twice the size, creating a Kosher paradise.
  • Glicks foundation has always been based on Superior Quality Kosher Meats. Since opening in Florida Gary has taken Glicks to a whole new level.
  • Famous for its outstanding meat department, Glicks sells thousands of fresh soups and prepared meals weekly. Glicks Deli Counter is second to none.
  • In store barrel cured deli meats, smoked fish and appetisers; including a sensational variety of over forty delicious homemade salads, hand rolled blintzes, homemade knishes, kreplach, petcha and scrumptious Matzo Balls are all a part of what makes Glicks a daily destination.

Wilmersdorfer Street-You're bucking for Israeli beer? Or do you urgently need a Kosher schnitzel for friends from abroad? Then you should definitely stop by in the largest Kosher supermarket in Germany. At first glance, the daily market in Charlottenburg looks like a normal supermarket. In the air lies the smell of detergents, bread and sweets, in the "Eingangsbereicht" is a pile of fresh fruit and vegetables, behind it there are wine, snacks and canned goods in the long shelf rows. It is only when looking at the labels that the assortment of well-known German brands is supplemented with numerous products from Israel. Hebrew letters and colourful packaging make the contents of many bags, boxes, and cans mysterious.
